<h1>Installation</h1>
<ul>
    <li><a href="#Linux">Linux</a></li>
    <li><a href="#OSX">OS X</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Windows">Windows</a></li>
</ul>

<a name="Linux"><h2>Linux</h2></a>
<p>Linux packages are compiled for CentOS 6.3 and may also work on other Linux
distributions.</p>
<p>

<p>To install the RPM package:</p>
<pre>
> sudo rpm -iv djv-@djvVersion@-Linux-64.rpm
</pre>
<p>To uninstall the RPM package:</p>
<pre>
> sudo rpm -e djv-@djvVersion@-1.x86_64
</pre>

<p>To install the DEB package:</p>
<pre>
> sudo dpkg -i djv-@djvVersion@-Linux-64.deb
</pre>
<p>To uninstall the DEB package:</p>
<pre>
> sudo dpkg --remove djv
</pre>

<a name="OSX"><h2>OS X</h2></a>
<p>OS X packages are compiled for OS X 10.7 and are compatible with later OS X
versions.</p>
<p>Shell scripts are provided to setup the proper environment and run the DJV
applications from a terminal, they are located in the "Contents/Resources/bin"
directory. For example if you installed DJV in the "/Applications" directory
use this command to run djv_convert:</p>
<pre>
> /Applications/djv-@djvVersion@-OSX-64.app/Contents/Resources/bin/djv_convert.sh
</pre>
<p>You can add an alias in your startup script (eg., $HOME/.profile) to provide a shortcut:</p>
<pre>
alias djv_convert=/Applications/djv-@djvVersion@-OSX-64.app/Contents/Resources/bin/djv_convert.sh
</pre>

<a name="Windows"><h2>Windows</h2></a>
<p>Windows packages are compiled for Windows 7. Note that only the 32-bit
versions of the Windows packages support Apple QuickTime.</p>

